q48_final_comments: CBD PARKING - With COVID-19 massively limiting public transport capacity (eg 12 people per bus v 60 normally), and with public transport into the CBD at 100%+ capacity in normal times (pre COVID), I believe now is the time for the City of Sydney to completely rethink its approach to parking in the CBD. In particular, I believe the Council should allow motorbike and scooters to park on selected footpaths and other  pedestrianised areas that are wide/big enough to accommodate such a move. For example, Martin Place could accommodate hundreds of bikes/scooters without impacting pedestrians. Such a move could open up more car parking spaces from the spaces currently used by bikes/scooters, and it could reduce road congestion as cars are replaced by bikes/scooters. I understand that Council does not allow such parking at present because of the perceived impact on pedestrians (inc. blind people), however I would simply say that a large number of countries/cities are the world cope very easily with such arrangements, particularly across Europe. Even Melbourne can do it so why can't we? Now is the time for some innovative solutions - not just the same old thinking which has been proven to be wrong (based on the experience in Melbourne and elsewhere). Thanks for your time.

q38_1_mostly_positive_changes:

 Make people kinder - to care more for neighbours - to be inclusive.  hopefully too for people to lift their hygiene levels - the number of cases of influenza have diminished.

q38_2_mostly_negative_changes:

 Risk is we see more racial vilification - ridiculous behaviour to medical staff.  People left with depression, anxiety due to fears about covid-19. As well as running online member catch ups and zoom catch ups to keep the community together and have our concierge team working remotely for them. q7_covid_impact_on_employment_l: I am the only employee and my entire industry (Live Entertainment and Events) is shut down. My business is not trading.
q10_business_still_operating: No - temporary closure
q11_12_reason_for_business_clos: There is no live event industry practicable under these conditions. Society and people need to reevaluate and find new ways. Online and video webcast concepts only employ a few people to run them. It does not replace or revive many jobs at all.
q12_what_could_have_helped_busi: A fast redevelopment strategy by government and private sector to transform the arts and live entertainment industry into a full digital and virtual platform with re training costs covered. A large spend on the infrastructure and technology needed to achieve this. A lot of people still got paid or had to work from home and will return after the restrictions are lifted. The arts entertainment industry will not switch back on at that time, It will take months longer to start up, and 12months to 2 years to begin to recover from the loss of so many operators, contractors, resources and people. The entertainment sector has needed an injection of sorts for over 10 years, relying on old television and newspaper style formats will not provide long term survival for this industry in Australia. If the car industry shut down here, there is no reason to believe arts and entertainment will survive here with our transformation.
q15_changes_made_to_business_ot: We have reduced fees and costs to zero dollars and are effectively working for nothing. We have as a business rent a total of $500 Australian since the end of January instead of about $100,000 in the same period last year. We are working with others to develop ideas, concepts, strategies and equipment to continue in the future as restrictions are lifted. Its obvious we can never go back the model we loved and have used since the 1920s. It's too big a gamble with the various insurance costs, liability and large taxes these days to proceed with large scale commitment that is needed to put on events, art exhibitions, performances, concerts and shows. The venues, theatres and cinemas need to be rebuilt and the concept of going out for the night or day needs a total rethink. We have also switched form 50 percent online meetings and office time to 100 percent only meetings, creative workshops and office time. Which is challenging with the fluctuations in service provided by the NBN. Getting a dedicated fibre line installed is costly and will cost between $600 and $900 per month to keep from any of the regular Telcos. everything that we can has been sold so a lot of valuable equipment and resource is gone, so when we do get to have events and shows again, it will be done with less effective technology and lower standards than before COVID 19
q16_collaborating_with_other_bu: Yes collaborating with all sorts of companies and artists with lots of ideas. But none of the businesses have any capital as they all went broke with no industry left at all. There simply are not enough grants to help, no one will qualify for one any way and there's no point without government and private sector support to redevelop entirely the way we put on shows and deliver the arts going forward in this century

q20_12_potential_support_from_c: find a way for small to medium live events to occur safely and cost effectively. Find a way to use the thousands of event and entertainment staff and crew to hold large scale occasions like australia day, chinese new year, New year eve, christmas etc. Maybe smaller displays and ideas in multiple locations all linked together with technology. Encourage the safe use of convention centres and halls again. Encourage the film and TV industry to get back to work in a safe and meaningful way.
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: time to move forward with new ideas. Time to leave the 20th century behind. Two way communication events and shows. Interactive and reactive performances that can adapt to comments and feedback in realtime. Its not enough to talk at or play to audience anymore. The attention span is short and the need to interact high. q38_2_mostly_negative_changes:
Fewer people travelling into the City for work and entertainment purposes. Those who previously would visit daily for work and would make the most of bars, restaurants and cultural activities will now be more likely to stay around their own neighbourhood, working from home where possible.
 Small local businesses that rely on the population and foot traffic are going to struggle to survive, particularly live entertainment, NTE, arts and cultural businesses.
 Coworking spaces re going to struggle to survive, with many residents deciding not to give up their space in favour of WFH. These spaces are critical to fostering innovation and creativity in Sydney.

q23_sector_change_post_restrict: A shrinking of the startup sector because there will be less capital available for early-stage companies. Angel investors i.e. high-income earners will use their bonuses to pay off their mortgages and save it for emergencies vs. investing in high-risk startups. VCs still have money for the coming year but will likely have more trouble raising it from limited partners such as pension funds (Hostplus being the major one) in the following year, which means less money will flow to VCs and subsequently startups. In order to keep Sydney competitively globally, the City needs to address this issue not by offering more coworking space and effectively competing with private organisations, which one can argue the NSW Government has done, but by supporting existing players. For instance through creating stronger international links to draw in international companies and investors a la the Victorian government.

It's ugly, badly designed and will only contribute to poor living standards for lots of people who already live here. Green Square station is already so congested that the platforms are often closed in peak hour as it is too dangerous - how is this area supposed to cope with an influx of more people. The roads are choked, there's nowhere to park, it's congested and noisy and ugly.

No one speaks to anyone around my area.

q33_7_are_there_any_positive_th: Gratitude that the world has slowed down a little - this has been very positive from my point of view, as a 65+ individual who is still working.  A trial run to transitioning to retirement and experiencing the small things in life in a positive way.
q37_17_what_concerns_you_most_a: Fear that our governments are making changes to legislation about planning without public permission or scrutiny during the COVID crisis, and that these changes will not be able to be rolled back once in place, leading to poor quality of life outcomes for our community in the future.
q38_1_mostly_positive_changes: Less crowding in streets and events, enabling people of different ages and physical abilities to participate in the vibrant community that the City of Sydney can offer.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes: Overcrowding of public transport is inevitable, given the number of workers and businesses that we try to cram into the City on a daily basis.  This will impact large businesses and building owners as they move elsewhere to conduct their business.  I am also concerned about the changes to Planning legislation that the NSW Govt is pushing through under the cover of darkness that COVID poses.  These do not sound like positive changes for the community, only benefiting developers in an anti-social way.  When will the people have a say in this and own their own future again?
q48_final_comments: Yes - my husband is 80 and needs to attend the Sydney Eye Hospital several times a month for Macular Degeneration treatment.  His is a case of "other use" of the City (ie, medical) which is not captured in this survey.  The Sydney Eye Hospital is the only public hospital that offers this treatment to patients, so people come from as far away as the Blue Mountains, Central or South Coasts.  These types of needs for elderly and disabled people need to be recognised, planned for and supported by governments and their planners.  Currently, they are not.  At its commercial level, this is a business transaction and many doctors are supported in a similar manner in the CBD by visits from elderly patients.  Just walk along Macquarie Street and observe.  They are there on their walking sticks, battling other pedestrians, no parking available for them, having travelled in to the City on public transport - the most dangerous place foer them to be in the time of COVID.  At a social level, this is a critical medical need.  I don't know the answer, but I'd like it considered in future planning.  Thanks.

I seek law makers to cease implementing the 180 days restriction to Sydney area to allow the much needed breathing space for small business owner like ours.

Climate change mitigation actions will receive lower priority. 
 
 Covid pandemic will be used as a rationale to push through laws & policies to boost the economy. This will facilitate activities that will further damage the environment & will receive less public scrutiny. Eg. increased fracking & coal mining, increased logging in significant natural areas, increased fire hazard burning for political reasons, diversion of water for agriculture for export including cotton farming from environmental flows. This will heavily impact Sydney's large population and have significant and long lasting political knock on effects to other states & territories .
 
 Covid virus is likely to be maintained in the dense & mobile population of Sydney for a very long time until "herd immunity" reaches a critical point and vaccines/therapies are developed and available to the general public.

q38_1_mostly_positive_changes:
Talking about the future
 
 There's a lot of discussion given voice in recent times about our future and what it can look like. 
 That always has been and always will be up to us. 
 
 We can continue with the “neo-liberal economic” stance with both its benefits and shortcomings or we can create something perhaps better and more whole and lasting.
 
 Somewhere along the way with our current values system we seem to have lost something called depth. Apparently most had been content to become good little consumers collecting stuff in our lives and the amount and type of that stuff defining who we think we are. Is this really enough?
 
 Isn’t there more to us?
 
 An interesting example came up this week with the City of Sydney facing the choice of accepting an attractive offer by retail giant Woolworths to extend their lease at Town Hall.  This would seriously postpone a long mooted project for an open Town Hall Square. That’s a daunting choice that I wouldn’t like to make. Either the money short term which is no doubt needed after the hit of Coronavirus or the civic community building project with its longer term benefits.
 
 Isn’t it time we asked ourselves who we are and what we stand for?
 
 We have literally become addicted to the immediate and shallow response to solve all our problems. Sorry but it ain’t working. Just look around.
 
 Many are saying that the bushfires and Covid 19 are warnings for us to take stock. Curiously isn’t that what Australia is doing in its calling for China to do with its role in the current pandemic? 
 
 It is far easier on the surface to go with the status quo than forge a conscious direction that would benefit us long term.
 
 I can’t help but say that if we continue on the path of habit then we can most probably expect more and increasing numbers of those “Black Swan” events that we have seen in recent times. This will eventually force us into unwilling and ultimately unhappy change anyway.
 
 This can be seen currently with China’s reaction in being called out. We are now it seems facing the mandatory action of diversifying our Trade markets. 
 Everything comes with its price.
 
 So are we going to go with the band aid of ‘business as usual’ or make a go of the long haul and probably short term thankless forging of a conscious direction as a more independent self aware nation in this Asia/Oceania region?
 
 I wonder what that proposed Town Hall Square might have to say about our future or will it be lost in the trampling of our insatiable want for more stuff?
 
 Regards,
 
 pastedGraphic.png
 
 NevilleWilliams
 8 Palmer Lane Darlinghurst NSW 2010 / Phone: (02) 9380 5486

q18_10_seeking_support_other:
Since, I'm a New Zealander, currently residing in NZ, I'm not eligible for any financial relief in NZ (have a subsidiary here), or in Australia.
 If I'd be residing in Australia, I would have been able to get a grant perhaps. 
 Can only take the $10k + $10k (2021), off my personal super, and qualify for a $10k company loan at zero interest from the NZ Government.

q38_1_mostly_positive_changes: There will be more remote-working from home or regional hubs. This will be a good thing because it allows working parents to save money on childcare and be less stressed by being bullied by bosses and sociopaths in the workplace in person; remote working will also reduce pressure on real estate prices because (1) CBD/inner city office space demand will lessen thus releasing more buildings for habitation (2) Living close(r) to work will not be of such importance hence people can work remotely from almost anywhere, including rural areas where r/e is far cheaper (3) Lessen pressure on public transport, roads, peak-hour traffic and reduce instances of driving under the influence of alcohol (4) lessen pressure on electricity supply due to reduced demand on air-conditioning in office buildingsespecailly 9–5,  as there will be fewer such office buildings. People will re-assess what is important to them after this enforced break; hence, fashion, overpriced restaurants, value-less entertainment, venues with overbearing goons will be patronised less. People will turn to rely on technology for social interaction and the latter will improve as a result of demand thus delivering better home movies and music, self-diagnostics, plus socialising and sharing via virtual presence, the devices for which I expect there to be exponential growth, such as Zoom, Whatsapp and the like, plus apps and gear not yet invented; the latter will make us more prepared and ready for the next pandemic – this is not a one-off. The world will change, no doubt about it.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes: There will be a social loss in people not being as keen to congregate. There will be a loss of privacy and further intrusion of governments, and their agents into people's private lives as part of the "positive changes" enumerated above by way of a Trojan horse. Old-style food markets may become less popular due to paranoia about becoming infected, so supermarkets will grab an even greater share of the food chain; this would be a bad thing because it would corporatise food even further, with negative consequences not just to consumers but primary producers as well. We know about this already. Chronic unemployment and casualisation of the workforce and inability for unions to be able to represent such workers as effectively as before. There will also be severe consequences for some people in terms of damage to their health which are not yet apparent and there are no provisions for that as far as I can see – Covid-19 causes long-term damage in some people in their organs such as liver, kidneys, heart and blood vessels. Hence, there will be pressure on the health system for dialysis, heart valve replacement and invaliding a sizeable proportion of society, which, added to an ageing population will assume an even greater burden.

q38_1_mostly_positive_changes: I hope we might enjoy a slower pace of life, less commuting/traffic in general, more local tourism rather than interstate/overseas, ongoing connectedness to our local communities, increased awareness of our collective fragility and the urgent need to mitigate climate change, prepare for more disasters, etc. I hope that more flexible work arrangements will continue and that fewer people will need to commute or to work 40 hour weeks outside of home.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes:
I think people could become more insular and self-protective.
 I'm worried there will be a return to over-consumerism and unnecessary travel (both locally using cars, and nationally/internationally via flying) as soon as restrictions are lifted.
 Also worried about the impacts of reduced public transport capacity due to social distancing. I think it's absolutely essential to do this and have no resentment towards the authorities limiting numbers of people on trains and buses. But the increased car traffic, parking issues and local environmental impact of more cars on the road could be awful.

q20_12_potential_support_from_c: Writers need writers festivals, obviously re-imagined for social distancing. We need bookshops and libraries (which often sponsor events) to be open. We need universities (a source of casual teaching or lecture gigs) to be funded and operational. Most of the work I've lost has been cancelled uni and festival and other speaking gigs. We also need our theatres to survive this and the ABC (another source of lost freelance income) to be able to commission local content. All of this combined has been a terrible blow. Obviously, when people's incomes are down, so is their ability or willingness to buy books. We need governments at all levels to express support for the arts, explain their value to Australian and community life and help re-imagine ways to keep our vital arts sector alive.
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: Enthusiastic government support in raising our visibility and credibility - no more bullshit about us being 'elites' from the true powerful and moneyed elites. We need to feel like we are being thought of as part of 'Team Australia', whatever that means. We need our important events and festivals and theatres and libraries fully funded, reimagined and up and operating. We need spaces like Carriageworks where new work can be performed, and festivals held.

q48_final_comments: If anything, the pandemic has shown that there is indeed overcrowding and unhealthy living standards globally, and that most govts are not prepared to step in with solid and reliable emergency plans for the good of everyday people, but will barter for positioning with big business to make a buck, erring on the side of $ than lives. Rating countries on their ability to handle covid19 reveals a lot about the general aspirations  and lack of foresight of a govt but not necessarily its people. There is much trust lost and rightly so, when we're asked to continue ' business as usual' after the pandemic. I don't know what the solution is, but I think a basic wage (means tested) for all Australian citizens and those with working visas could be the start of something good for people. Endless, circuitous form-filling for grants to find out you're not eligible is so disheartening, why bother? I ranted on for another 20minutes, but deleted it all, lucky for both of us, as this will probably end up on some dead end anyway. But thanks.

 Negative changes to workplace protections and privacy laws, etc, from the government, post-shutdown.
 Lobbying from dying industries like fossil fuels leading to wasted public funds pumped into economically-unsound mining and fossil fuels projects leading to increased pollution and delayed change and innovation to the energy industry in this country.

q15_changes_made_to_business_ot: Tried to promote to local community that we were open when stage 3 closures were in place. This was hard due to Government and media communication not being clear and lot of people had no idea that they could go to their local cafe, in doing this the Government and media had severely damaged our ability to respond and potentially reduce any impact. The limit in cashflow meant we could not promote the business effectively. We didnt think it was a great idea to incur more debt to pay for such services for little to no return.  Changed cafe to allow pick up and social distancing can be achieved as per health departments advice.   Have looked at ways to grow the ecommerce side of the business through sourcing technological resources that avoid incurring costs to the business. Have found a free operating system now as there was no positive benefit to use apps like Uber, menulog or bopple as the Government was not clear with the message and slow to implement social benefits which are not high enough to maintain confidence. Unlike in China where people are in lockdown and have a better universal income for those that lost jobs, currently online delivery is booming.  We are looking at different food options we can offer to the local community with the likes of pre-prepared meals and other areas where others havent grown their business with.  We have lost a major market share with gyms closing and corporate offices relocating their staff at home which wont go back to normal for a long time. So we really need to expand our reach to different emerging markets like work from home employees needing delivery of goods and services

q15_changes_made_to_business_ot: Firstly, the AFC has been affected by a significant reduction in business memberships. Existing AFC members have struggled to pay their renewal fees since March due to their businesses being severely affected by Covid-19 (including retail trade restrictions, cancelled wholesale orders, delays in stock shipments etc). We have also been unable to bring on new members due to the same reasons.  Secondly, our local TCF industry required immediate help with how to adapt their business structures during the pandemic. This has meant that the AFC has had to dramatically shift it's day-to-day activities and roll out new initiatives to address the industry's immediate concerns and needs. As a result, our staff have had significantly increase their workloads to adapt.  Thirdly, due to the loss in membership revenue and a lack of immediate financial resources from sponsors and grants, the AFC team has had to reduce their working days by 20% in April and 33% from May. Taking into account the second point above, this has proven difficult to manage effectively.
q16_collaborating_with_other_bu: 1. Education We have been running a series of webinars to address industry concerns during this time and to help businesses plan for recovery over the next 6-12 months. This has been in a multiphase approach - Response, Recovery and Revival. So far, we have run webinars in collaboration locally based business and organisations, including, McKinsey & Company, The General Store, Marque Lawyers, MWAH, Ernst & Young, Fabric Agency and Smart in Planning. This webinar series will continue over the next few months.  2. Industry Survey Last month the AFC put out a 'COVID-19 Australian TCF Industry Survey' to all our networks. From this we have been able to understand the huge impact this crisis has had on our fashion & textile industry and the need for the AFC, as the peak industry body, to be the voice for the Australian industry. We produced the results for this survey in collaboration with McKinsey & Co.  2. Virtual Tools  In collaboration with Ordre we have recently launched AFC Virtual, which we will be heavily focussed on growing from June onwards. The AFC Virtual X ORDRE platform will create an important business gateway and valuable opportunity for Australian designers by way of a virtual showroom to connect directly with buyers. Buyers will be able to review collections, make selections and place wholesale orders online, having access to individual designer virtual showrooms which incorporate product information and a range of digital images and videos (produced in their Sydney Office).  3. Think Tank The AFC will also bring together key industry stakeholders and international creative thought leaders, in the form of a Think Tank, to establish a future strategy to help the industry pivot to the post-Covid-19 world. This is to keep across the industry's concerns and keep businesses up to date with the latest updates and opportunities.
q19_7_seeking_small_business_gr: We are technically listed as a Victoria based organisation, although half of our team is based in Sydney and we run most of our programs from here. We have applied for the Vic Gov grant but are not eligible for the NSW Gov grant.
q19_8_seeking_grant_support_fro: Our application was denied, although unsure of the reason at this time.
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: Our industry is looking for support across a range of issues; financial, from both local and federal government, operational, with clear rules and guidelines around post-lockdown reactivation, and strategic, for pivoting and reviving businesses.  Broadly, businesses are calling for financial assistance in a timely manner that caters to the needs of the TCF sector, and in hope that it will continue once the immediate health threat is controlled, allowing time for the industry to recover.  The industry is also looking for demand support through the prioritisation of locally made and sourced products, as well as fostering collaboration across sectors and within the industry. Key sentiment from industry calls for; <U+25CF> Government investment in local manufacturing with incentives, and a nation wide review of procurement guidelines <U+25CF> Fashion festivals, retailers and industry bodies to advocate for and prioritise local design and manufacture <U+25CF> Initiatives supporting diversification of local capabilities, up-skilling workforces and job creation <U+25CF> Strategic market guidance - what to anticipate on the other side of Covid-19 and how to best prepare - eg. digital strategy, merchandise planning and reaching local and global markets  There is clear opportunity in (and a desire for) our industry coming together, calling for collaboration within and across sectors. We have identified a common prospect for pooled resources and industry joint ventures to modernise Australian manufacturing and become globally competitive. Collaboration is even more apparent as an opportunity for smaller brands and sole traders; from co-working spaces, to overcoming MOQ’s, to joint workshops and co-owned assets and equipment.  Our industry has voiced a renewed energy for investing in Australian supply chains, in-house manufacturing, hiring more staff locally and becoming vertically integrated. Note has been made of the opportunities that would come from better connecting manufacturing capacity/capability with demand, from recognising and working toward bridging the gaps in the local supply chain. There is significant opportunity for government investment and process reviews to support the sector through this crisis and into a globally competitive future; from local government tenders prioritising locally made goods, through to PPE production and support for the industry to adapt to diverse and economically and environmentally sustainable manufacturing needs.  Overall, our industry has identified a desire to nurture the demand for Australian designed, owned and made TCF products. Global consumer markets and retailers stand to provide new sales avenues for Australian fashion. There is great potential for the Government to support activities to increase the global awareness of Australian fashion brands as well as assisting in the creation of group opportunities at international fashion and trade events. Diversifying markets and product offering, pivoting production capabilities and creating and growing digital realms of business are common themes identified by businesses as future opportunities for growth. Drivers identified included partnering with other e-commerce retailers, reinventing online business models and expanding offerings to include services and knowledge.   From any crisis emerges a need to rethink current systems and create new business models. Embracing more sustainable practices, working toward a circular economy and shifting the dial on recycling fashion waste are central to many of our businesses' outlook for the future. Note has been made of investment in smart infrastructure, clean energy, tech innovation, using more Australian natural fibres, building regenerated and recycled fibre processing capacity, and the need for State and Federal Government policy to support the implementation of a product stewardship scheme, similar to that implemented on e-waste and plastics. There is also a desire to set progressive and aspirational policy to incentivise industry to address climate change through adopting the United Nations’ Sustainable Development Goals and Paris Climate Agreement targets.

q48_final_comments: Please put the brakes on more approvals for large (10+ dwelling) construction sites and give the long suffering residents some reprieve from the noise (including construction vehicles kerb crawling for parking from 6.20am, huge trucks on small streets delivering building materials and reversing at 6am waiting for sites to open, endless crane sirens and clicking etc).  Being at home all the time now it's hard not to notice that we are completely surrounded by construction sites, noise and overdevelopment lining the pockets of foreign investors.  There are 3 cranes visible from my rear yard.  We can't drive anywhere because we cant get a parking space when we come back home until after 6pm when everyone has finished work for the day.  Walking is less enjoyable because Sydney park is overcrowded but the back streets are too dark, abandoned or have incomplete footpaths due to construction.  Development in Alexandria doesnt benefit those who live here, only those here to make a quick buck, or those commuting through.  Completing our daily activities is becoming much more difficult and tedious than it should be.

q20_12_potential_support_from_c: The laws imposed on Hotels for trading are a huge factor in our general day to day trading. However coming out of this, if they were to be eased it would be a huge benefit to the business. As an example we require a security guard to be on site Thursday through to Sunday, even though we are the only pub in the area that has this on our license as well as never having an issue in which security was required and/or police have been called to assist with removing or dealing with a patron. It's just a little ridiculous.
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: Be a little more switched on with how rules are regulated & linked to licenses. It can't be a one size fits all, or a matter of applying post a certain date changing the outcome.  We should be able to operate and offer the public a fun & safe environment  & not have to explain regulations placed upon us by council & governemnt that make absolutly no sense. IT makes us look like idiots when we need to explain that patrons can't; - sit out on a table on the street having a beer & a feed or smoke, but the pub across the road can; or - sit at the bar with their dog while they have a drink but dogs are allowed in the courtyard; or - be able to have any form of speakers outside areas, even though we are at least 15m from the nearest residential area (more noise from the street than from us; or - having to have security Thursday through Sunday because we opened March 2018. YEt the pub across the road or down the road doesn't have to, even though our dining clientele would be considered the least likely to cause issues; or  I'm all for laws & regulations that are required to make sure that venues operate & handle themselves correctly. However not every venue is the same, some venues have well trained staff, good clientele, proper procedures in place to deal with all issues & cater to a crowd that won't be causing issues.

q33_7_are_there_any_positive_th: At first yes - my mindset was looking forward to the lock-down. I work from home mostly anyway and a good local community (I have a great employer who has always enabled me to work flexibly once family started expanding).  I was expecting a sudden drop-off of work and a likely 6 month stop after the Ruby Princess debacle looked like NSW would be heading down the same path as the US and Italy and there may be time to get some home projects completed. There has been a definite slow-down (construction and architecture) - no new projects - but work already in the pipeline has continued.  Once that's done over the next couple of months, I'm expecting my income is very likely to decline dramatically. I love family yet surprisingly have found having an extra 4 extra people now living and working in the house has been incredibly disruptive to my productivity.  Way more of a domestic burden (unshared) and lots of interruptions.  Our office also had to be set-up for everyone else to work from home, which ended up being disruptive technically, and having most of NSW on the internet has been a nightmare not being able to upload files or get timely access to files.  Australia has to fix this infrastructure! A disaster from the Abbott years of federal government and unfortunately tasked to Turnbull to wreck, who gets the blame now.
q38_1_mostly_positive_changes: I hope there will be changes that see our LNP governments finally acknowledge that a recovery lead by a construction boom in affordable and social housing is an easy-to-roll-out no-brainer that will tick every health, wellbeing and ultimately every economic box possible.  I hope that business and financiers will become the loudest voices in a need to address climate action through the funding and approval of renewable projects and infrastructure upgrades to support it rather than holding up fossil fuel industries.  I hope that workplaces will enable more flexible conditions that help everyone better balance home and work time and responsibilities.  I hope that government will acknowledge Australia cannot function effectively into the future unless our internet/wifi is capable.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes: However, the influence of vested political interests are driving the recovery particularly at national level.  This is a terrible direction for the national recovery and will set us back decades as far a climate action is concerned if they are not challenged and public money does flow to them as proposed currently. Industries currently shaping our future are those that further increase GHG emissions, advocate to remove any effective governance (of the little that remains), remove environmental protections, and happy to lead us towards further inequalities between working Australians and big business interests.  This is not a good direction for a cohesive society and ignores the vulnerable.  The NSW Planning Minister fast-tracking approvals is appalling.  Unless a project is fully compliant with our PUBLIC policies, they should be automatically excluded from this pathway.  I also worry that women will lose decades of progress fighting for an equal workplace given changes to childcare  (already unsustainable) appear more likely will impact on the primary caregivers who are overwhelmingly women being able to participate in the workforce.  This has clear productivity issues that government must address.
q48_final_comments: Thank you for the City of Sydney's unparalleled leadership during the whole of Clover Moore's time as Lord Mayor.  The public interest is well advocated and the community particularly those most in need are well-served.  There is much work to do in this space. The city itself has seen many excellent public initiatives - not all perfect but it remains one of the best performing and professional Councils.  Thank-you, your hard work is greatly appreciated and is making long-term positive contributions to our city-making.

Loss of income / employment,Worrying about the security of my job ,Stress caused by living and working in close proximity to others ,It was difficult to navigate public space during lockdown, in particular the parks. Rushcutters Bay became a no-go for some. Parks were crowded, gyms had moved their fitness training outside; there was little adherence to the social distancing rules and it was so stressful, I know a lot of people wouldn't risk it. It was clear in this densely populated urban space (Kings Cross/ Potts Point), we need open green space and for our parks to be safe places.  Even the small street parks.  This time demonstrated how key our connection to nature is.
q33_7_are_there_any_positive_th: The drop in pollution, traffic noise and noise like yelling and screaming.
q37_17_what_concerns_you_most_a: Entertainment and going to bars, clubs and restaurants is not the same as "cutural expression".  We don't have enough cultural life going on in the City of Sydney. There are not enough cinemas.  We have the big galleries but not enough of a cultural infrastructure. There's not enough affordable housing for writers, creators and artists living in the city.   Design businesses are not the same thing as making art. Hot desks and offices to share is not the same thing as studios.  It seems that a lot is geared to protecting and promoting the night economy but not the arts.
q38_1_mostly_positive_changes: I hope for greater action on climate change.  More focus on how we live: with nature in our cities, creating, giving.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes: I don't see the negative other than people's capacity to earn a living. The loss of jobs and impact on arts companies has obviously been devastating.

q4_3_business_overview: Provide inspiration and share creativity through my artistic designs at The Rocks Markets.
q7_covid_impact_on_employment_l: As a sole trader (no option for this in the previous question) with a business in hibernation, I am working pretty much my usual hours with about 5% of my usual income.
q10_business_still_operating: Yes - in a limited or changed way
q15_changes_made_to_business_ot: As I can't actually sell my work at the moment face to face (the market is closed and customers are not allowed) I am forced to find alternative ways to generate an income with what I create so I'm trying to find ways to do this, make the changes to my website (which hasn't previously been focused on retail sales of my porcelain and art works because of the costs involved in online marketing etc), promote it and develop the skills (although developing skills and delivering on new products/ideas is the easiest part as I do it regularly). So I am having to significantly change my business with what I can sell, how to sell it and how to deliver it. I need to do this because it would be very foolish of me to think The Rocks Markets will recover within 12 months of it starting up again.
q16_collaborating_with_other_bu: Yes, online with a dedicated Facebook community group of us artisans and artists showcasing our work (although I am struggling with having the right sort of images at this stage for this, I am learning and making progress but the income certainly isn't there) and we are being very supportive of each other with sharing skills, ideas and connections.
q18_10_seeking_support_other:
Job Keeper came out too late, is too complicated and there was no way to properly understand it during the initial weeks and I had rent to pay a nasty type of landlady (first time I've had a nasty type). So I had to get Job Seeker ASAP as I had Sydney rent to pay. While Centrelink is obviously designed to be difficult to work with, I've had financial help LONG before anything could have come through Job Keeper.
 As for an unsecured business loan there's no way I would consider taking on debt without knowing what my future may or may not hold, that would be foolish and irresponsible of me. And I'm a sole trader who's an artist, which organisation would even look at me? 
 There are no state or federal government grants open for me as a sole trader without employees. It was very lucky to find the CoS grants but they'll be over subscribed to and with little chance of getting simply due to the numbers. I do appreciate that the CoS thought of us though.
q19_2_seeking_rent_relief_from_: She is greedy and nasty
q19_3_seeking_debt_relief_from_: Coles Mastercard don't really want to do this so they are making the process very difficult.
q19_5_seeking_jobkeeper_benefit: Too complicated and way too delayed, I had to go to Job Seeker immediately (23rd March but did it in an area out of Sydney so I didn't have to line up)
q19_6_seeking_tax_relief_from_f: The ATO have been great to work with when you can get through.
q19_8_seeking_grant_support_fro: Fingers crossed but not a lot of hope because there'd be a GREAT DEAL of competition as the demand is so high
q19_9_seeking_unsecured_busines: Not a clue how to pay anything back and who would loan to a small business at the moment?
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: I'm not sure about the term "sector". I'm probably thinking far more local than that. At The Rocks Markets us stall holders have a problem with Property NSW selling our market footprint to festival organisers, eg. the Christmas in July man, St Patrick Day drinking area, Ockoberfest drinking area, where they push out the majority of the small creative businesses who make up The Rocks Markets so we don't get to trade for an entire weekend. This is all in the name of activation (a bit of a dirty word when it costs you income and makes you struggle to pay your Sydney rent). There are 3 areas to our market - the canopy, Playfair St and Jack Munday. The Jack Munday area has been significantly reduced due to new outdoor dining setups and the Overseas Passenger Terminal trucks needing access now that we have trams again. So we understand that area of market needs to be flexible and this can also include selling it to the festival owners. But it isn't acceptable to sell off Playfair Street and/or the Canopy areas for festivals and denying us the opportunity to earn our living. But as small businesses and as artists our voices are too small to be heard, we're told we're heard but it's too late to change the festival contract - EVERY time, EVERY year. So my hope is that as we return to market and life post covid that the festivals and activations aren't too big, that maybe, just maybe, governments and their employees may understand the impact felt by loss of income. But I could easily be too naive with this.

q37_17_what_concerns_you_most_a: Loss of biodiversity. This is different to the question above about loss of green spaces for recreation. We need to enhance and create new connected areas with rich endemic habitat wherever possible, in public and private spaces. This can help create Community as well as have biodiversity gains. Any development should not be allowed to remove existing plants (especially native ones) and new landscaping should accord with ecological recommendations
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes: Sadly, the need to distance ourselves for months or years, until treatment or vaccines are developed, may permanently be the loss of our spontaneously warm, close, hugging nature! Also if the Federal and state governments prioritise business as usual in the recovery (especially fossil fuel business) rather than innovative and environmentally sustainable actions, we will have missed the best opportunity to change for the better, for reducing climate change impacts and improving biodiversity. People in the arts/music sector are clearly in trouble and this may reflect in reduced opportunities in the future too. People in disadvantage and with mental health issues will likely be having even further difficulties unless wonderful positive projects are implemented.
q48_final_comments: Thank you. I want to add that now that the whole population is seeing how important it is to listen to scientific advice, based on the best research and evidence, it is really important to grasp this opportunity to increase their level of scientific thinking and knowledge in other fields (especially environmentally) and to help everyone know how to do evidence-based decision-making in every aspect of their lives. This is vital for governments at every level! Here is an nternationally recognised health example https://training.cochrane.org/essentials

Our staff incentives are tied to KPI's they are now no longer able to achieve due to decreased utilisation rates because of social distancing.
q18_10_seeking_support_other:
Other grants for SME's, grants for retraining older employees, accessing superannuation.
 The other support we require is ways of dealing with staff, creating staff engagement.  Some have become quite difficult to deal with and are making unreasonable demands.
q19_2_seeking_rent_relief_from_: The landlord is non responsive to requests for relief and has indicated that he is in financial trouble and not in a place to provide us relief.  We are giving him a final opportunity to reply to our requests this week. If we don't hear from him we will request mediation.
q19_3_seeking_debt_relief_from_: ANZ have been shockingly bad.  We have been a customer for over 22 years and their responses to our requests for assistance were terrible. We have $20K debt on a credit card that we wanted to refinance to reduce interest payments and pay down but they have not been amenable to many of our requests.  They were also really slow in responding to our initial requests for assistance.
q19_4_seeking_payroll_tax_relie: This has taken a long time to be received.
q19_8_seeking_grant_support_fro: We just received an email saying I was unsuccessful with no explanation.
q19_9_seeking_unsecured_busines: We are trying to obtain this so we can refinance and restructure
q19_10_seeking_support_other_st: Grants often require a lot of financial information that is not available at the time of application eg tax returns etc.
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: More support for employers trying to deal with staff who are belligerent and unreasonable.  More advocacy for employers about HR challenges with staff (not all of us a arseholes like the ABC tries to make out).  Better ways of managing suppliers and landlords who are really difficult to deal with by being unsupportive, unresponsive or just plain inconsiderate. Safe Work Australia recommendations are completely at odds with SME's who run on very tight profit margins so we need to be able to run a full book of clients to survive. Cheaper rents. Government support for businesses who are employing people on an ethical basis - ie tying support to employers who can provide evidence that all employee entitlements are paid (ie super). Making (UN)Fair Work Australia more fair for employers - stop making changes to the law that increases employment costs for employers... stop putting the burden on employers all the time.

q38_1_mostly_positive_changes:
I hope there has been opportunity for our city to reflect on our incredible fortune to have managed well through this Global Pandemic; and yet also that we have lost many in Sydney, NSW and Australia. I hope that this leads to positive change; a realisation that we are truely dependent upon one another for our wellbeing, that our consumption-driven lifestyles are leading to more and more disasters for our country and world (the bushfires and COVID both exacerbated by the conditions this lifestyle has formed). 
 I hope that we can be be well-led by electing appropriate leadership to carry us forward from here, but with this I hope we are more civically engaged citizens who are community minded, generous and tolerant.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes: So much about the 'way of life' was already tettering on the edge of functional. Sydney is, culturally, heavily work focused and has bought into a rat race more than any other city - and yet we have exquisite beauty that we should treasure more and should in theory slow us down. with this, our culture is less generous and community-minded, and the flow ons include wide inequality, little-to-no affordable housing and no sense of government support for the management of these important issues - if anything, State and Federal governments would encourage this to grow deeper, but the ramifications will be negative. Social inequality is slated to expand, and these aforementioned conditions look likely to deepen, solidify and become even more the 'norm' if left unchecked.

q48_final_comments: 1. This is a time for adaptation and innovation. An opportunity to partner with game changers. The City can help by streamlining approvals, fee concessions, engaging with local business, property and home owners who are willing to personally invest in development, growth and green spaces. Grants should be issued cautiously and avoid being wasted on business that won't survive.  2. Use of outdoor space will become important for offices and street level food/bev businesses. Approvals for utilizing outdoor space needs to be prompt and encouraged. Allow small businesses to invest in outdoor street dining, or office towers to start projects like converting rooftop spaces.  3. More tables in public parks. Use of parks has surged and will likely continue because outdoors is safer.  4. Encourage home owners to spend on renovation works.

q37_17_what_concerns_you_most_a: We've been really lucky that we've had such a great, transparent and responsive local government. I fear losing our independent and strong local government.
q38_1_mostly_positive_changes: Greater appreciation for the outdoors, for the simple pleasures of walking in a park and getting some fresh air. An amazing ability for us to all cooperate and help each other. We've all gained new knowledge from this new experience.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes:
People wanting to "go back to normal" like it was the best place for Sydney to be. I think its time to re-evaluate. My biggest concern is for local businesses, especially retailers. I feel there is an opportunity for Australia to harness the "communal energy" from COVID-19 and start reinvesting in Australia. I think we need to focus on local production (that's ethical and environmentally friendly) and support the community as we all re-focus on a "better future" - it will require, re-skilling/up-skilling and lots of grants to help individuals and businesses reinvent themselves. If that can happen, the negatives are few for me.
 
 I worry about my lack of knowledge and understanding of people who have been badly affected by COVID-19. Either I have yet to meet them or I live in an overly privileged socio-economic bubble.....

q23_sector_change_post_restrict: I think the current model doesn't really reflect the way people actually work currently or should be in the future at all.  This is especially true for contractors and sole traders.  I find it interesting that government at all levels wants to contract rather than employ services mainly I know to have these expenses sit against a different line item for accounting purposes other than salary, wages & related on costs.  However it hasn't progressed away from the very archaic unionised 9-5 employee or pty ltd company model.  This needs to change as there are many of us in the middle who literally can't move.  Tax incentives for contracts, agency hire and sole traders need to be there to actually properly self manage their own leave to draw on when needed.  Also we should have to pay ourselves minimum super.  Its all very well to say 'you get a loading' as casual or self employed but there needs to be incentive on managing that well and clarity that is the expectation. I also think the way government uses labour hire on set contracts desperately needs to be reviewed.  Individuals should be able to register as sole traders and contract directly. Its madness that employees can enter enterprise bargaining under an award but self employed can't negotiate their own contracts directly - defies the purpose of being self employed & means government are missing out on a massive talent pool of people. Many like myself who left, are very experienced & get locked out because the recruitment industry seems to be mostly run by young international working visa people who don't understand either the busienss need nor the skills of candidates. The amount of jobs people would specifically like me for but can't engage me due to some over complicated process and protocol is ridiculous because the reality is they have no control of who they employ.  It is desperately broken, needs to be totally reverse engineered and modernised.  Anyway... I could go on... I mean you did ask!

q23_sector_change_post_restrict: We want to see the end of 'battery farm' coworking spaces that undercut privately owned coworking. These spaces have traditionally had a monopoly by designing spaces with small desks/small offices so that they can reduce costs by 'quantity' which advocates unhygienic conditions and undervalues the industry. The monopolies in our industry create an unrealistic idea of what the 'actual' cost of managing a desk and environment are.

q48_final_comments: The only thing I’d like to highlight is that during the height of the pandemic, when Australian began lockdown, aligned communication was lacking. Brainstorming ways to let the community know WHY they can and cannot do certain things is imperative so we can educated each other properly. Seeing signs that say “make sure your sanitise” & and “keep 1.5m apart” is great, but I think we need to educate the public with signs that describe HOW this virus moves and spreads — as the information comes to us. This, to me anyway, is more impactful. If I saw a diagram of how this virus spreads or how quickly it moves or stays in one area, I would pay far more attention and take the “1.5m distance” even more seriously— generally speaking. I’m a 27 year old male and the age groups 18-35, are fearless. I’m worried as we reopen bars and clubs, my demographic will forget that. Showing us WHY & HOW from a verified source (City of Sydney) that’s fact checked and easy to read on-the-go will resonate more for us and get the message in our stubborn heads. That goes for the oldies that think they know everything, too! It’s cool to be informed

q10_business_still_operating: No - temporary closure
q12_what_could_have_helped_busi: We will reopen but with trade so low due to the city being empty of office workers we will likely not survive. We have outdoor style restaurant that needs a full summer trade to make through winter. We’re now forced to try and make it through winter with restrictions and no business trade around. After building up debt from 9 weeks of closure having to still pay so many costs. Restaurants have one highest labour costs of any industry. All we’d need is our payroll tax for the year back and we might have some hope. The entertainment fringe tax benefits to be rolled back so that corporates can spend with us when they do return. Our industry has a workforce that is 75% not eligible for Jobkeeper how do we operate again with such little help from the government to get going. I feel it’s almost hopeless and after a decade of owning, operating restaurants my husband and I will be out of a job as will our employees so of which have worked with us a decade. More needs to be done for restaurants to make it. The worst is yet to come. The next 6 months will be a tale of restaurants closing leaving thousands out of work.
q15_changes_made_to_business_ot: We have provided ready to heat meals and groceries but as a restaurant in the cbd trade is very low. Residential restaurants are doing better during this pandemic as they have local residents to sell takeaway too. Cbd restaurants were the first hit and the will be the last to get customers back.
q20_12_potential_support_from_c: ,Scrapping fringe benefit tax so corporates can spend and scrapping payroll tax on small/medium businesses like restaurants
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: The last question did not have enough responses. Even at stage 3 we are restricted and not viable as the 1 per 4 square metres leaves us with only 25% of our capacity.  Payroll tax needs a much higher threshold  Fringe benefit taxes need to be addressed  Restaurant Employment awards need to be addressed they are faulted and means the best of us need to spend on employment lawyers to try and get it right. It shouldn’t be that difficult

Lack of access to public libraries. The closure of Sydney’s Paddys markets for fresh produce. Cancellation of in person group parenting course.
q33_7_are_there_any_positive_th: Lower transport emissions in the city area. Less exhaust fumes. More enjoyable footpaths and parks not being ringed by engine noise or exhaust fumes. More families outside enjoying time with their children. Less hectic/stressed life due to most community sports/activities ceasing. Better and improved healthiness of my family and kids due to schools taking (finally a zero-tolerance to respiratory illnesses and symptoms). Much safer cycling with children. More access to open public spaces previously crowded by outdoor tables and or smokers (e.g. the 100s of tables that line the eastern boulevard at Circular Quay permanently or the pub tables on the corner of Elizabeth and Goulburn Streets on an already very narrow footpaths. Less tired husband at home after work (working from home) due to no mental energy expended for work travel or dealing with the ‘office environment’. Husband better able to mentally engage positively with the children after his day working from home. Seeing that governments at all levels (across the political spectrum) can cooperate with one another. Seeing that governments can make quick and effective decisions and changes that are evidenced based. Less rampant consumption of fossil fuels. Families having more time to prepare more healthier meals at home. Less reliance on unsustainable economic practices e.g. importing fresh flowers through jet transport from Africa and South America! No gambling in the city - saving people’ thousands of $$. Less opportunity for our unsustainable drinking cultures and more opportunities for individuals to devote to the quality of their lives and relationships.
q37_17_what_concerns_you_most_a: Lack of pathways for apartments to invest in renewable energy generation. Lack of planning requirements for developers to incorporate solar passive design and renewable energy generation.
q38_1_mostly_positive_changes: More time for individuals to reflect on the quality and sustainability of their own lives and relationships. Governments making evidence based decisions in a timely manner for the benefit of the community.
q38_2_mostly_negative_changes: Loss of need for hectares of corporate floor spaces in the CBD with work from home opportunities being a viable alternative.
q48_final_comments: The city could take the opportunity (with NSW transport) to return much of the city’s roads to pedestrian and cycling use as the car traffic has dramatically reduced.

q4_3_business_overview: Live music performance; research, curation, teaching
q7_covid_impact_on_employment_l: I am a freelance musician with a portfolio career. I am a sole trader working on contract for S2M performance companies right round Australia; I am also a casual payroll employee of the Sydney Symphony, and The University of Sydney, Sydney Conservatorium of Music. I am also a part-time PhD student at Sydney Uni, so I can keep my sessional casual contract at the Uni. My PhD is working with Sydney Living Museums, and working on the music collection of Rouse Hill House & Farm; but I have also worked for SLM when it was HHT, and been a guide and acting assistant curator for the Museum of Sydney & Government House Sydney, before the Governor was moved back in there...
q10_business_still_operating: Yes - in a limited or changed way
q15_changes_made_to_business_ot: We are almost entirely online - performing where venues have livestreaming, and are able to ticket and monetise to help artists. Not enough venues in Sydney are able to do this yet. Melbourne Digital Concert Hall is leading the way with this. I am also an artistic curator with St James King St Sydney, and we are investigating using their livestream system, currently focussed on delivering church services; to delivering its concert program - and an expanded concert program - to help the NSW based S2M music companies particularly. But St James needs help with its digital set up and web master services - we have one person doing it, and they are not experts. I am also teaching at Sydney Conservatorium, The University of Sydney - which has gone entirely online for Semester 1. I am VERY grateful for a recent successful grant application to CoS Arts funding, to help a project with Sydney Living Museums deliver an online public program in engagement with the music collection - COS is to be commended for its swift action to help the arts sector pivot to new methods of delivery. I used to teach in a philanthropically funded program run by the Australian Chamber Orchestra, for children at St Marys North Public School, which was string instrumental learning to help low ses students with literacy. But this has been cancelled by ACO and we have been sacked (we were casual) - I'm guessing due to company funds being very precarious.
q16_collaborating_with_other_bu: Yes. [personal data withheld] - funded by recent CoS funding round [personal data withheld] - digital public engagement using the music collection of [personal data withheld]. Also collaborating with [personal data withheld] to deliver the concert program via online livestream instead of face to face, to assist the S2M arts sector in NSW.
q18_10_seeking_support_other: Have applied for Australia Council Covid grants - unsuccessful. City of Sydney grants - successful THANK YOU! Create NSW - application pending. JobKeeper - not eligible as I am too complicated a mix of short and long term contracts for arts companies and payroll casual for universities and MPArts companies such as Sydney Symphony. JobSeeker - may have to try this in the long summer non teaching period from university, as there is and will be no performance income to build up the usual holiday period buffer than a freelance needs to survive
q19_5_seeking_jobkeeper_benefit: Not eligilble - freelance artist with work a nightmare mix of short and long term contracts for arts companies; plus casual payroll work for the [personal data withheld]
q19_6_seeking_tax_relief_from_f: Not eliglble - yet - my accountant says I may be. I have lost somewhere between $40 - 80K depending on how long the arts and academic sectors take to pick up
q20_12_potential_support_from_c: ,Arts sector initiatives to encourage State and Federal government policy makers that entertainment involves more than just opening up NRL football again!!!!!!
q23_sector_change_post_restrict: That the arts matter to the australian voting population...We feel ignored, demoralised, and that we are not wanted in Australia by the Coalition Federal governments actions during the pandemic, and in the years since Howard, particlularly since 2013. This period has seen a decimation of Australia's intellectual life and the arts, and we are all terrified about getting some sort of cultural sector back up and operating again. Thank you to the City of Sydney Council who truly see that arts are not only important to the Australian economy, but vital to a 'living city' and to the population's well being. Arts Music in general needs more help with digital upskilling, and collaborative ideas,  to deliver concerts online to an audience with an average age of 61, who may be more wary of joining live concerts and events after Covid restrictions are lifted for younger audiences.

q15_changes_made_to_business_ot: •Placing more emphasis on the take away/delivery aspect of the business due to restricted numbers of dine-in patrons.  •Creation of new product lines to expand the revenue base for the business. •Applying for government grants and benefits to assist with cash flow where eligible (e.g. JobKeeper, ATO cash flow boost, NSW small business grant etc.). •Increased hygiene and sanitation measures as well as social distancing will be implemented to provide a safe environment for diners and encourage increased patronage of the restaurant. **We've done all the above changes and end up closing the business temporarily as the running cost is very high such as utilities,insurance, wages, telecommunications etc.. the takeaways were nominal in comparison to the dine-in operation.
